  "summary": "During a dinner at a restaurant, Charles proposes marriage to Sophia. Sophia hesitates, explaining that her grandfather’s death has complicated their future. She reveals her suspicion that her eighty-five-year-old grandfather did not die of natural causes but was murdered, a suspicion shared by a doctor who refused to issue a death certificate. Sophia notes that because Charles is a diplomat, her family's sensitive situation could impact their marriage. She warns Charles that they are being watched, identifying a man resembling a retired soldier in a blue check suit who followed her from Stewley Station. To meet Charles, Sophia had to climb out of her bathroom window and down a drainpipe. She urges Charles to seek an unbiased perspective by asking his father, an assistant to the Commissioner at Scotland Yard.\n\nUpon returning home, Charles visits his father in his study. Charles reveals that he has met Sophia and describes the man following her. His father expresses concern, noting that while the Leonidis family is of noble lineage, the current circumstances are problematic. His father cryptically suggests that Charles should only marry her if the person who killed the grandfather is \"the one.\" The passage ends with his father questioning how much Charles actually knows about the situation.",
